# AGENTS.md â€” working in {{name}}

This is the agent doctrine for **{{name}}**, a project driven by
[pyclawd](https://github.com/{{owner}}/pyclawd) â€” a project-generic Python
dev-task CLI. One config file (`.pyclawd/config.py`) describes the project, and
humans and AI agents drive it the same way. This file is the commands-first
contract for agents; `README.md` covers the human-facing overview.

## Critical rule â€” how to run Python

**ALWAYS run Python through `pyclawd python`. NEVER call bare `python` / `python -c`.**

```bash
pyclawd python script.py          # run a script
pyclawd python -m pytest ...       # run a module
pyclawd python -c "import {{pkg}}" # quick check
```

`pyclawd python` runs in the project's configured env (the `conda_env` in
`.pyclawd/config.py`, or whatever env pyclawd is installed into) with the repo
root on `PYTHONPATH`. Bare `python` misses the env and the in-tree source.

## Commands â€” quick reference

| Task | Command |
|---|---|
| Resolved config (what each command runs) | `pyclawd config` |
| Health-check the dev env | `pyclawd doctor` |
| Run Python in the env | `pyclawd python <file>` Â· `-m <mod>` Â· `-c <code>` |
| Fast smoke (<30s, no integration) | `pyclawd test fast` |
| Default gate (no slow, integration OK) | `pyclawd test run` |
| Full suite (incl. slow + integration) | `pyclawd test all` |
| Select tests | `pyclawd test -k <kw>` Â· `pyclawd test tests/path::node` |
| Fix-loop | `pyclawd test failures` â†’ `pyclawd test fix` â†’ `pyclawd test run` |
| Lint / autofix | `pyclawd lint` Â· `pyclawd lint --fix` Â· `pyclawd lint <file...>` |
| Format / check | `pyclawd format` Â· `pyclawd format --check` Â· `pyclawd format <file...>` |
| Type-check | `pyclawd typecheck` Â· `pyclawd typecheck <file...>` |
| **Aggregate quality gate** | `pyclawd check` Â· `--fix` Â· `--skip <verb>` Â· `--fail-fast` Â· `pyclawd check <file...>` |
| Build / dist / clean | `pyclawd compile` Â· `pyclawd dist` Â· `pyclawd clean` |
| Manage agent skills | `pyclawd skills list` Â· `pyclawd skills install` |
| Repo root / version | `pyclawd root` Â· `pyclawd version` |

`pyclawd check` runs all quality steps (format-check â†’ lint â†’ typecheck)
**regardless of individual failures**, then **test** (only if quality passed). Each
failing quality step is tee'd to a log file whose path appears in the summary â€”
read those files to see the full output. Use `--skip <verb>` (repeatable) to omit a
step entirely, `--fail-fast` to stop at the first failure, and `--fix` to apply
format+lint autofixes in-place before checking. Build/dist/clean and docs commands
only do real work when the project configures them; otherwise they degrade
gracefully. Override config discovery with `--config PATH` (or `PYCLAWD_CONFIG`);
by default pyclawd walks up from cwd to find `.pyclawd/config.py`.

## Test tiers â€” what each runs

| Tier | Marker filter | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `fast` | `not slow and not integration` | After every edit â€” <30s smoke |
| `run` (default) | `not slow` | Before opening a PR |
| `all` | _(no filter)_ | Nightly / pre-release |

Mark slow tests with `@pytest.mark.slow`, tests needing live services with
`@pytest.mark.integration`. Unmarked tests run in every tier. Never mark
tests `@pytest.mark.fast` â€” unmarked is the default.

## Prerequisites

pyclawd orchestrates tools; each command needs its tool present (run `pyclawd
doctor` to see what's missing). Typically: **pytest** for `test` (+ pytest-xdist
for `test fast`), **ruff** for `lint`/`format`, **mypy** for `typecheck`. If this
project builds docs, `pyclawd docs render` also needs the **pandoc** system binary
and a `./docs` runner, and `pyclawd docs failures` needs **jupyter-cache**. The
exact tools live in `.pyclawd/config.py` â€” that file is the source of truth.

## Architecture â€” generic core + per-project config

pyclawd ships a project-agnostic command layer. Everything project-specific lives
in **`.pyclawd/config.py`** â€” a module-level `project = Project(...)` (from
`pyclawd import Project`). The directory containing `.pyclawd/` **is** the repo
root. The `Project` model groups config: `QualityConfig` (lint/format/typecheck),
`TestConfig` (tests dir + tier markers), `DocsConfig` (or `None`), `DoctorConfig`
(deps/binaries to probe). Read `.pyclawd/config.py` before assuming how this
project is wired â€” it is the single source of truth for env, paths, and checks.

**Every module** opens with a one-line docstring. `pyclawd ls --missing` finds
gaps â€” keep it empty. **Docstrings use Google style, no types** (annotations are
the source of truth; `pyclawd lint` enforces via `D`/`DOC` ruff rules):

```python
def foo(x: int) -> str:
    """One-line summary.

    Args:
        x: Description (no type â€” it's in the signature).

    Returns:
        Description of the return value.
    """
```

NumPy-style (`Parameters\n----------`) will fail `pyclawd lint`. Tests are
exempt from docstring rules.

## Boundaries

### Always
- Run code via `pyclawd python` â€” never bare `python`.
- Run `pyclawd doctor` first when the env looks off or tests fail to import.
- **Run `pyclawd check` before declaring work done** or opening a PR.
- Fix the **cause** of a failing test, not the assertion â€” tolerances for floats,
  pinned seeds for stochastic tests.
- Match existing patterns; read `.pyclawd/config.py` before changing wiring.

### Ask first
- Destructive cleans (`pyclawd clean --ext`), committing, pushing, opening PRs.
- Changing `.pyclawd/config.py`, dependencies, or the public API surface.

### Never
- Never call bare `python`/`pip` outside the project env.
- Never commit secrets, tokens, or credentials.
- Never weaken or delete a test to make a suite pass.
- Never leave the tree with a failing `pyclawd check`.
- Never use `git commit --no-verify` to bypass pre-commit hooks â€” fix the underlying issue instead.

## Existing repos â€” quality baseline

If `pyclawd check` is red on a repo you didn't just scaffold, it has a
pre-existing quality backlog. **Do not reformat or re-lint files you aren't
otherwise touching** â€” that inflates your diff with unrelated churn and makes
review harder.

Two paths:

**A â€” Preferred: land a baseline PR first** (one commit, zero logic change):
```bash
pyclawd format          # reformat everything
pyclawd lint --fix      # autofix all fixable lint
pyclawd check           # now green; gate is live for all future work
```

**B â€” If the baseline PR is too disruptive right now**: scope quality checks
to only the files you are changing:
```bash
pyclawd format src/mypkg/mymodule.py
pyclawd lint   src/mypkg/mymodule.py
```
Your changes stay clean; the repo-wide backlog is a separate concern. Document
in your PR description that the repo has a pre-existing quality backlog.

### Docstring convention â€” opting out or changing

The scaffold defaults to **Google style** enforced by ruff `D`/`DOC` rules.
For repos with an existing convention, configure it once in `pyproject.toml`
â€” no docstrings need rewriting:

```toml
# NumPy-style repo (scientific / pandas / numpy ecosystem)
[tool.ruff.lint.pydocstyle]
convention = "numpy"

# No docstring enforcement (legacy codebase, gradual adoption)
[tool.ruff.lint]
ignore = ["D", "DOC"]

# Enforce style on existing docstrings but don't require them everywhere yet
[tool.ruff.lint]
ignore = ["D100", "D101", "D102", "D103", "D104", "D105", "D106", "D107"]
```

> **Before writing any docstring:** read `pyproject.toml` to check which
> convention this repo uses. Match the existing style â€” don't convert.

## How you know you're done

- `pyclawd check` is green (format-check, lint, typecheck, and tests all âś“).
- `pyclawd doctor` exits 0 â€” no FAILs.
- Behavior is verified by tests, not just by inspection.
